---
import CaseStudyLayout from '../../layouts/CaseStudyLayout.astro';

const data = {
  metaTitle: "Quoting & Estimating Tool for Custom Home Builder | All Webbed Labs Case Study",
  metaDescription: "How an Adelaide custom home builder cut quote preparation from 3 days to 4 hours, reduced client query calls by 71%, and prepared twice as many quotes in the first month on the platform.",

  industry: "Construction & Trades",
  tags: ["Quoting & Estimating", "Client Portal", "Xero Integration", "PDF Generation", "Variation Management"],

  title: "Quoting & Estimating Tool",
  summary: "An Adelaide custom home builder producing 18 to 22 homes per year replaced inconsistent Excel-based quoting and email-chain variation management with a purpose-built estimating platform and client portal — cutting quote preparation from three days to four hours and doubling monthly quote output.",

  heroImageDescription: "Builder and client reviewing a detailed home construction quote on a laptop in a modern site office, with architectural plans spread on the table beside them",

  // CASE_STUDY_PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client details when approved
  clientOverview: "Cornerstone Homes SA is an Adelaide-based custom home builder with eight staff building 18 to 22 homes per year at price points between $600,000 and $1.4 million. The company works predominantly in the Hills district and the inner eastern suburbs, with a reputation for detailed architectural work and a client base that expects a premium experience from initial enquiry through to handover.",
  clientSize: "8 staff · 18–22 homes per year",
  clientLocation: "Adelaide, SA",

  pullQuote: "We were turning away clients because we physically didn't have time to prepare quotes. The quoting process was the bottleneck that was limiting our revenue, and we'd accepted that as normal. The idea that we could do the same quality of work in four hours instead of three days took a while to sink in, but that's where we've landed.",
  pullQuoteAuthor: "Director",
  pullQuoteRole: "Cornerstone Homes SA",

  challenge: [
    "Every quote at Cornerstone Homes was built from scratch in Microsoft Excel. There was no standard template — different estimators had different spreadsheet structures, different trade rate assumptions, different conventions for how to handle inclusions and exclusions. The director had created a master template years earlier that was nominally the standard, but it had been copied, modified, and diverged by each estimator until the 'standard' existed in five different versions. A quote prepared by one estimator couldn't easily be reviewed or updated by another, and when the two estimators compared notes on similar jobs, they regularly found material pricing discrepancies of five to eight percent.",
    "Material prices were a persistent problem. Trade pricing in South Australia, particularly for timber framing, concrete, and insulation, fluctuates meaningfully across quarters. The Excel spreadsheet contained static material prices that were manually updated — in theory monthly, in practice whenever someone remembered. When the director reviewed a job that had been won six months earlier and was starting construction, he sometimes found that the material prices in the original quote were no longer accurate, creating margin erosion that wasn't visible until the job was underway. On two occasions in the previous two years, jobs had been delivered at a loss because of material price movements that hadn't been reflected in the original quote.",
    "The client experience during the quoting process was a source of regular dissatisfaction. After submitting a quote request — typically a set of architectural drawings and a specification document — clients had no visibility of where their quote was in preparation. The typical client rang the office three to four times during the 10 to 14 business days it took to produce a quote, each call requiring a staff member to investigate where the quote was up to and provide an estimate of completion. The director had received direct feedback from clients who hadn't proceeded that the communication during the quoting phase had damaged their confidence in how the company would communicate during the build.",
    "Variations during construction — changes to scope, material selections, or specifications requested by clients — were managed entirely by email. A client would email a variation request, the estimator would price it up, send an email back with the cost, and the client would reply with approval or a counter-question. The approval was an email reply. When disputes arose — and they did, particularly with variations that had ripple effects on other elements of the build — the history lived in an email thread that was hard to navigate and didn't clearly document what had been approved at what price and by whom. Under the South Australian Building and Construction Industry Security of Payment Act 2009 and the General Conditions of Contract used in residential construction, proper variation documentation isn't just best practice; it's a contractual and legal requirement.",
    "Invoice reconciliation at project completion was genuinely difficult. The final invoice needed to reflect the original contract price plus all approved variations, less any provisional sums that had been resolved at a different value than estimated. Assembling this reconciliation required the bookkeeper to work through the complete email variation history, the original quote document, and the Xero transaction records simultaneously. On a complex home with 15 to 20 variations, this could take a full day. Cornerstone had experienced one formal dispute with a client over final invoicing where the inability to produce a clear variation log in a timely way had damaged the company's negotiating position."
  ],

  whyUs: [
    "The director had been considering a custom quoting tool for two years but had never committed to it. His concern was that any system he built would lock him into workflows that might not match the way quoting actually needed to work for custom architectural homes — where no two jobs are structurally the same and flexibility in the line item structure matters. He'd seen two building industry SaaS platforms that had fixed estimating templates and found them constraining.",
    "The conversation with All Webbed Labs came through his accountant, who had referred another trade client to us six months earlier. The accountant's framing was useful: rather than pitching us as a software company, she described us as people who would actually understand the business problem first. The director's initial call was exploratory rather than a brief, and we spent most of it asking him to describe the quoting process in detail — what made custom home quoting different from volume production work, how he managed the complexity of provisional sums for client selections, and what the variation management problem actually cost him in disputes and reconciliation time.",
    "We proposed a three-phase build that matched the company's appetite for change. Phase one was the quoting engine and client portal — replacing Excel and giving clients visibility. Phase two was variation management with digital approvals. Phase three was Xero integration and final reconciliation. Each phase was priced and scoped independently, with phase two and three contingent on phase one proving out in production. This approach let the director get value quickly and make an informed decision about the deeper integrations before committing to the full scope."
  ],

  approach: [
    "The discovery phase focused heavily on understanding the data model for a custom home quote. A custom home quote isn't just a list of materials and labour rates — it's a hierarchical structure of trade packages (earthworks, concrete, framing, roofing, external cladding, internal fit-out, and so on), each of which contains line items that may be fixed price, provisional sum, or prime cost. Provisional sums and prime costs are estimates that will be resolved at actual cost during the build, and how they're handled in the original quote document and then tracked through variations has real legal implications for the contract.",
    "We built a detailed entity model for the quoting structure before writing any frontend code, and validated it with the director and his senior estimator over two sessions. This validation process caught an edge case that would have caused problems: the company's quotes sometimes included 'allowance items' that were neither provisional sums nor prime costs in the strict contractual sense, but were client-visible budget placeholders for items not yet specified. These needed to flow through to the client portal clearly labelled as allowances, not confirmed prices. The distinction mattered for client expectations and for the company's exposure under the South Australian consumer protection provisions that apply to residential building contracts.",
    "The material price feed integration required more research than expected. There's no single industry feed for South Australian construction material pricing. We identified that the best available data came from the company's existing supplier accounts — their three main suppliers all had pricing APIs or exportable price lists available to account holders. We built the integration around those three supplier accounts specifically, with a weekly automated import and a manual override capability for items where the company had negotiated rates below catalogue pricing. The director reviewed the approach and confirmed it was how the company actually purchased — making the price feed directly relevant to actual job costs rather than a generic index.",
    "The PDF generation requirement was non-trivial. Cornerstone's quotes needed to look like premium documents — not a generic software printout. The director showed us three previous quotes as examples of the standard he wanted to maintain, and we used Puppeteer with a carefully designed HTML/CSS template to produce quote PDFs that matched the company's existing visual quality. We iterated on the template through four rounds of design review. Getting the document design right was almost as important as getting the data right — the quote document was the most significant sales artifact the company produced, and downgrading its visual quality would have been commercially damaging."
  ],

  solution: [
    "The quoting engine is a React web application with a structured line-item entry interface that replaces the Excel spreadsheet. Trade packages are set up as reusable templates with the company's standard line items and current material prices pre-populated — an estimator building a standard residential quote selects the applicable packages and adjusts quantities, rather than starting from a blank page. The system enforces consistent rate structures across estimators while allowing override at the line-item level for unusual specifications.",
    "Material prices are synchronised from the three supplier feeds weekly, with the system displaying the current price alongside any manual override and flagging items where the supplier price has moved more than five percent since the quote was last updated. When an estimator re-opens a quote after a period where prices have changed, they see a price drift alert before proceeding — a deliberate friction point that prevents quotes from being sent with stale pricing without a conscious decision to proceed.",
    "The client portal gives each prospective client a private, password-protected link to their quote as soon as it's published by the estimator. The portal displays the quote in a structured, readable format — not the raw line-item detail, but a clean summary view by trade package with the total broken down into fixed-price items, provisional sums, and prime costs, each category clearly explained. Clients can see the quote status (in preparation, ready for review, accepted, expired), download the formal PDF, and submit questions that route directly to the estimator. The portal eliminated the 'where's my quote?' calls because clients always knew the current status.",
    "Variation management, delivered in phase two, replaced the email chain with a structured approval workflow. Variation requests can be initiated by either Cornerstone staff or the client through the portal. Each variation has a scope description, price impact, and any upstream effects on provisional sums or adjacent trade packages. When submitted for approval, the client receives an email with a portal link to the variation detail and an explicit approval or rejection button — not an email reply chain, but a button that records the approval with a timestamp and the approving party's identity. The complete variation register, with all approved, rejected, and pending variations in chronological order, is available to both the Cornerstone team and the client at all times.",
    "The Xero integration, delivered in phase three, connects the quoting system to Xero's invoicing API. When a quote is accepted and converted to a contract, the corresponding Xero project is created automatically with the approved contract value. As variations are approved, they're added to the Xero project record. When a provisional sum is resolved at the actual cost, the system records the resolution and updates the Xero project value. At practical completion, the system produces a reconciliation summary — contract price, plus all variations, plus provisional sum resolutions, minus any credits — and creates a draft final invoice in Xero with all line items pre-populated."
  ],

  techStack: [
    { name: "React", reason: "Builder admin interface and client portal — component-based architecture suited to the complex, dynamic quoting form" },
    { name: "Node.js", reason: "REST API and background jobs for price feed imports and PDF generation queue" },
    { name: "PostgreSQL", reason: "Hierarchical quote data model with full version history for variation audit trail" },
    { name: "Puppeteer (PDF Generation)", reason: "Pixel-accurate PDF output from HTML/CSS templates matching the company's existing document visual standard" },
    { name: "Material Price Feed Integration", reason: "Weekly automated price imports from three supplier APIs; eliminates stale pricing in quotes" },
    { name: "Xero API", reason: "Automated project creation, variation tracking, and final invoice generation at practical completion" },
    { name: "AWS", reason: "EC2 hosting, RDS for PostgreSQL, S3 for generated PDF storage and document attachments" }
  ],

  implementation: [
    "Phase one went live after fourteen weeks of development. The rollout started with the director using the system himself for two weeks on live quotes before bringing the senior estimator on board. This wasn't just about training — it was about the director being able to speak from personal experience when the estimator had questions or concerns. The estimator's primary concern was whether the system would accommodate the variation in quote structures across different project types. Within the first week she had found two edge cases — both involving sub-packages for landscaping that Cornerstone optionally included in some contracts — and we resolved both within three days of them being reported.",
    "The client portal adoption was immediate and positive. The director sent the portal link to the four clients in active quoting when the system launched. All four engaged with it — two submitted questions through the portal within 24 hours, replacing calls they would otherwise have made. The director described this as 'surprising' because he'd half-expected clients to prefer the phone. In practice, clients appreciated being able to review the quote at 9pm when they had the time rather than calling during business hours when they were at work.",
    "Phase two — variation management — required a change management conversation with existing clients who were mid-build when it launched. We'd anticipated this and built a migration path: existing variations documented in email threads were entered into the system by Cornerstone staff, with the original email approval noted as the documentation source. Two clients had questions about why the process was changing mid-project; both accepted the explanation that the new system would make variation tracking clearer for both parties. Neither experienced any disruption.",
    "The one implementation challenge we hadn't fully anticipated was the provisional sum resolution workflow. In practice, when a provisional sum for, say, kitchen cabinetry is resolved at a higher-than-estimated actual cost, the process isn't a clean single transaction — it often involves multiple supplier quotes, a negotiation with the client, a credit for part of the original allowance, and a new charge. The initial data model treated provisional sum resolutions as single events. We had to extend it to support multi-step resolution records after the first real-world resolution exposed the limitation. This added two weeks to the phase three timeline."
  ],

  lessonsLearned: [
    "The document design effort — getting the quote PDF to look right — took longer than we budgeted and is work we now cost more carefully in proposals for similar projects. In industries where a document is a primary client-facing artifact, the design of that document isn't a cosmetic concern; it's part of the product. We went through four rounds of revisions because the early iterations, while functionally correct, didn't feel premium. The difference between a quote that looks like it came from professional estimation software and one that looks like it came from a tradesperson's invoicing app is commercially significant for a company operating at the $600K to $1.4M price point.",
    "The material price feed integration surfaced a business insight that the director found uncomfortable but valuable: the company's negotiated rates with their primary concrete supplier were actually higher than the catalogue prices listed in the supplier's API after a pricing restructure that had happened eight months earlier without anyone at Cornerstone noticing. The estimator had been using the old rates from the Excel spreadsheet and inadvertently overbidding on concrete-heavy jobs. Identifying this was a direct result of having a system that pulled and compared live pricing data, and it led to a commercial conversation with the supplier that the director hadn't thought to have.",
    "We initially built the client portal as a read-only view with a questions form. Phase one went live this way and worked well. But within the first month, two clients asked whether they could make selections — choosing from kitchen or bathroom finish options, for example — directly in the portal rather than emailing a list of choices. This was a natural extension of the variation workflow and was added in phase two. The lesson was that clients, given a portal experience that worked, would naturally want to do more through it. Building a portal and treating it as a one-way communication channel is an underutilisation of the investment."
  ],

  whatCameNext: [
    "In the six months following the phase three go-live, Cornerstone's quote output doubled — 22 quotes in the first month on platform versus 11 in the same month the prior year, a direct result of the time savings in preparation. Revenue pipeline visibility improved significantly; the director could see at any given time how many quotes were in preparation, how many were with clients pending acceptance, and what the total potential contract value was. He described this as 'running the business like a business rather than a building site.'",
    "The company is now exploring using the variation and provisional sum data from completed projects to improve their initial estimates for similar future projects — essentially a feedback loop where actual job costs inform future provisional sum allowances. This is a feature we've scoped but not yet built; the data is accumulating in the system and will support it when the company is ready to invest in the analysis layer.",
    "Two other custom builders in the South Australian market have asked Cornerstone's director about the system. He has referred both to All Webbed Labs. We're considering whether a multi-tenancy version of the platform — a shared SaaS product for small custom builders — would be a commercially viable extension of the work already done."
  ],

  resultsNarrative: "In the first month on the platform, Cornerstone prepared 22 quotes — exactly double the 11 prepared in the same period of the previous year. Quote preparation time dropped from an average of three days to four hours. Material pricing errors have been zero since the price feed integration went live. Client query calls during the quoting phase dropped by 71%. Variation approval time fell from an average of five business days to same-day for straightforward variations. The client satisfaction score in post-contract surveys reached 4.8 out of 5.",

  metrics: [
    { value: "4 hrs", label: "Average quote preparation time", context: "Down from 3 days — an 83% reduction" },
    { value: "2×", label: "Monthly quote output", context: "22 quotes in first month vs 11 in same period prior year" },
    { value: "71%", label: "Reduction in client query calls", context: "During quoting phase — client portal visibility" },
    { value: "Same-day", label: "Variation approval turnaround", context: "Down from average 5 business days" },
    { value: "Zero", label: "Material pricing errors post-launch", context: "After live price feed integration from 3 suppliers" },
    { value: "4.8/5", label: "Client satisfaction score", context: "From post-contract surveys, platform cohort" }
  ],

